titleproper.value:
Guide to the William A. Reuben Papers
                    <num>TAM.289</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Evan Daniel

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2012-03-29T19:19-0400</date>

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value:
William A. Reuben (1916-2004) was a graduate of Columbia University and a World War II combat veteran. After the war Reuben began his career as an investigative journalist. Reuben's first book on the Alger Hiss trials, 
                <title render="italic">The Honorable Mr. Nixon</title>, was published in 1956. Shortly after this, Reuben began his reexamination of the Hiss case evidence, a task that would occupy him for the rest of his life. In 1974, as part of this work, he filed a Freedom of Information Act request for FBI documents related to the case. The release of such documents, and the information they provided, enabled Alger Hiss to prepare a lawsuit seeking to overturn his conviction based on an alleged pattern of misconduct by the Bureau and the prosecutor, Thomas F. Murphy. The collection consists of correspondence, reference materials, drafts of several unpublished book-length works by Reuben, copies of FBI and other government files, and copies of court records. Also included are one box of audiotapes and one boxes of research notes. 
                <emph render="bold">NOTE: This collection is stored offsite and advance notice is required for use.</emph>
                <emph render="bold">NOTE: For series one, researchers should use the microfilm (R-7771E).</emph>

p.value: <emph render="bold">NOTE: This collection is stored offsite and advance notice is required for use.</emph> Researchers must use microfilm for Series I, Box 1 (Film R-7771E). There is a published guide for the microfilmed portion of the collection (call number REF E743.5.H55 P38 2006). The guide also details portions of other collections related to Alger Hiss at this repository which have been microfilmed.

Published citations should take the following form: 
                <lb/>
                <lb/>Identification of item, date; Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; 
                <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives 
                <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library 
                <lb/>70 Washington Square South 
                <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.
William Reuben died of natural causes on Monday, May 31, 2004, in New York City, at the age of 88.
<emph render="bold">NOTE: This collection is stored offsite and advance notice is required for use.</emph>
